subSubSection.paragraph:
Scolytus tsugae
is an uncommon and poorly studied species. The adult galleries are typically perpendicular to the grain of the wood and 4.0-10.0 cm in length (Fig. 25) (
Edson 1967
; 
Furniss and Johnson 2002
). Adult galleries score the cambium slightly more than the sapwood. However, 
Edson (1967)
reported that specimens from a series in northern California produced an adult gallery that was oriented obliquely to the grain of the wood. Galleries consist of a central nuptial chamber and two egg galleries. Each egg gallery is extended perpendicular to the grain of the wood from the central nuptial chamber. Egg niches are irregularly spaced and faintly score the sapwood. Larval tunnels are extended parallel to the grain of the wood, etching the sapwood lightly at first and deeply near the pupation chamber. There is one generation per year and broods overwinter as larvae (
Furniss and Johnson 2002
).
